==English==
===Forms and variants===
*[[ha'porth]]

===Etymology===
Abbreviated from '''[[halfpennyworth]]'''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈheɪpəθ/}}, {{SAMPA|/"heIp@T/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

#{{UK}} A [[halfpennyworth]].
#*'''1838,''' [[w:Charles Dickens|Charles Dickens]], ''[[w:The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]''
#*:'Mighty fine certainly,' said Ralph, with great testiness. 'When I first went to business, ma'am, I took a penny loaf and a '''ha'porth''' of milk for my breakfast as I walked to the city every morning; what do you say to that, ma'am? Breakfast! Bah!'
#*'''1853''', Mansfield Parkyns, ''Life in Abyssinia'', John Murray 1853, p. 83
#*: I have frequently sat in his shop watching the passers-by [...] while the worthy little man was dealing out farthing-worths of pepper and '''ha'p'orths''' of sugar.
#{{UK}} {{slang}} A [[foolish]] person.
#:''daft ha'p'orth'', ''silly ha'p'orth''
